<subSubSection id="C35436B80B08FFC5FF18BD89948AAE7D" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B08FFC5FF18BD89948AAE7D" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,1100]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FF18BD899736AF80" bold="true" box="[136,375,158,184]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Description:—Plant</emphasis>
forming extensive clumps of spreading pads (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B08FFC5FC0ABD8995B2AF80" box="[922,1011,158,184]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1072,1094]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,294,1048]" captionTargetId="figure-21@26.[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Opuntia dillenii (Hoxey 1695.04) with Frigate Island, off the south coast of Carriacou." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420351" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420351/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FB9ABD88920CAF80" box="[1034,1101,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Joints</emphasis>
obovate to oblong, epidermis blueish green and glaucous. Areoles evenly spaced with white felt. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FCFABDD595F2AFE4" box="[874,947,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Spines</emphasis>
stout, 2–10, usually curved, yellow. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FAD6BDD693EAAFE3" box="[1350,1451,193,219]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Glochids</emphasis>
numerous, yellow, appear from upper edge of areoles only (but occasionally absent). 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FBC2BDF292F0AFC7" bold="true" box="[1106,1201,229,255]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Flowers</emphasis>
usually appear on the edge of the pads. yellow (orange-yellow on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FDE1BC1F949CAE1B" box="[625,733,264,291]" name="Barbados" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Barbados</collectingCountry>
) petals. 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FCA9BC1F95C3AE1A" bold="true" box="[825,898,264,290]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Fruits</emphasis>
(when mature) 
<quantity id="4CB6C8D60B08FFC5FBA2BC1F92C5AE1A" box="[1074,1156,264,290]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" unit="cm" value="8.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.0">7–9 cm</quantity>
long, purple red, juicy red pulp, usually spineless but with numerous glochids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35436B80B08FFC5FF2DBC5992ACAEEA" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B08FFC5FF2DBC5995FCAE97" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,1100]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FF2DBC599496AE50" bold="true" box="[189,727,334,360]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
Distribution in the study area (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B08FFC5FDB3BC5994EAAE50" box="[547,683,334,360]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[185,1410,205,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[170,1417,190,1928]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of cacti on Barbados, Grenada, Saint Vincent and the Grenadine islands based on observations by the authors. A. Acanthocereus tetragonus. B. Cereus repandus. C. Mammillaria mammillaris. D. Melocactus broadwayi. E. Melocactus intortus. F. Opuntia dillenii. G. Pilosocereus curtisii H. Selenicereus plumieri I. Opuntia dillenii (Barbados). J. Pilosocereus barbadensis (Barbados)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420304/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Figs. 2F–2I</figureCitation>
):—
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FD47BC5895C6AE50" authorityName="Haworth" authorityYear="1819" baseAuthorityName="Ker Gawler" box="[727,903,334,361]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dillenii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FD47BC5895C6AE50" box="[727,903,334,361]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Opuntia dillenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found on most of 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FBF3BC599352AE50" box="[1123,1299,334,360]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">The Grenadines</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FAD5BC5993E6AE50" box="[1349,1447,334,360]" name="Grenada" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Grenada</collectingCountry>
, but not on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FE90BC6697DAAEB3" box="[256,411,369,395]" name="Saint Vincent and the Grenadines" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Saint Vincent</collectingCountry>
. It also occurs on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FDF3BC669491AEB3" box="[611,720,369,395]" name="Barbados" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Barbados</collectingCountry>
. On 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FC94BC66952FAEB3" box="[772,878,369,395]" name="Barbados" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Barbados</collectingCountry>
we only found the species on the north coast of the island, growing on coral limestone and in the 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FD19BC8294AAAE97" box="[649,747,405,431]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Scotland</collectingCountry>
sandstone district.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B08FFC5FF2DBCAF92ACAEEA" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,1100]" box="[189,1261,440,466]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FF2DBCAF9799AEEA" bold="true" box="[189,472,440,466]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">General distribution:—</emphasis>
This species is widespread in the Lesser Antilles and Greater Antilles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35436B80B08FFC5FF2DBCCC943AAB74" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B08FFC5FF2DBCCC9498ADD3" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,1100]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FF2DBCCC9720AECD" bold="true" box="[189,353,475,501]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Discussion:—</emphasis>
We agree with the taxonomic treatment by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B08FFC5FCDDBCCC9274AECD" author="Howard, R. A." box="[845,1077,475,501]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" refId="ref17132" refString="Howard, R. A. (1989) Flora of the Lesser Antilles, Vol. 5. President and Fellows of Harvard College, Jamaica Plain, Massachusetts, 604 pp." type="book" year="1989">Howard (1989: 412)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B08FFC5FBFDBCCC93EAAECD" author="Taylor, N. P. &amp; Zappi, D. C." box="[1133,1451,475,501]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" refId="ref18333" refString="Taylor, N. P. &amp; Zappi, D. C. (2004) Cacti of Eastern Brazil. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, 497 pp." type="book" year="2004">Taylor &amp; Zappi (2004: 192)</bibRefCitation>
who recognized 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FED4BCE897B6AD20" authorityName="Haworth" authorityYear="1819" baseAuthorityName="Ker Gawler" box="[324,503,510,537]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dillenii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FED4BCE897B6AD20" box="[324,503,510,537]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Opuntia dillenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a separate species widespread in the Caribbean region. On the other hand, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B08FFC5FAE3BCE8970AAD04" author="Hunt, D. R. &amp; Taylor, N. P. &amp; Charles, G." pageId="25" pageNumber="50" refId="ref17306" refString="Hunt, D. R., Taylor, N. P. &amp; Charles, G. (Eds.) (2006) The New Cactus Lexicon. Text. dh Books, Milborne Port, England, 373 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Hunt 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FF18BF359680AD03" box="[136,193,545,571]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">et al.</emphasis>
(2006: 202)
</bibRefCitation>
suggested it may just be a spiny form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FC8ABF359584AD03" box="[794,965,546,572]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stricta">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FC8ABF359584AD03" box="[794,965,546,572]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Opuntia stricta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We consider 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FBF4BF359294AD03" authorityName="Haworth" authorityYear="1819" baseAuthorityName="Ker Gawler" box="[1124,1237,545,572]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dillenii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FBF4BF359294AD03" box="[1124,1237,545,572]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">O. dillenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a native species of the Lesser Antilles. Note however, that the fruit is sweet, edible, and a useful as food source, so it may have been introduced by human at least in some sites. Early settlers could easily have dispersed this species by transporting pads as they travelled amongst the islands. Nevertheless, it is probably dispersing itself naturally now as we encountered the species on small islands of difficult access (e.g. Pigeon island off Bequia) which is unlikely to have been inhabited, and local people take little interest in the plant today.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B08FFC5FF2DBFE2926CAC6D" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,1100]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
The flower of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FEF3BFE29457AC37" authorityName="Haworth" authorityYear="1819" baseAuthorityName="Ker Gawler" box="[355,534,757,783]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dillenii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FEF3BFE29457AC37" box="[355,534,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Opuntia dillenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reported to be yellow, but on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FC1CBFE295B7AC37" box="[908,1014,757,783]" name="Barbados" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Barbados</collectingCountry>
it is orange-yellow coloured. We only saw flowering plants on Union Island (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B08FFC5FDD5BE0F94D6AC0B" box="[581,663,792,819]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="26.[136,229,2002,2024]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1120,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-40@26.[151,1436,1120,1978]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 25. Opuntia dillenii (Hoxey 1676.03) yellow flower, Union Island." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420353/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FD49BE0F9502AC0A" box="[729,835,792,818]" name="Barbados" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Barbados</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="137579B60B08FFC5FCC4BE0F95E7AC0B" box="[852,934,792,819]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1072,1094]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetId="figure-17@27.[151,1436,190,1048]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 26. Opuntia dillenii (Hoxey 1708.02) with orange flower, Barbados." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420355" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420355/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
) and confirmed this observation. Most plants had green immature fruits but occasionally we found mature purple fruits (
<figureCitation id="137579B60B08FFC5FC5DBE2C9260AC6D" box="[973,1057,827,853]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="27.[136,229,2002,2024]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1120,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-31@27.[151,1436,1120,1978]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 27. Opuntia dillenii (Hoxey 1704.05) pad with typical spination and ripe fruit, Ronde Island." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5420357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5420357/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF165330B08FFC5FF2DBE4994A9ACDA" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,1100]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B08FFC5FF2DBE4997E7AC41" author="Howard, R. A." box="[189,422,862,889]" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" refId="ref17132" refString="Howard, R. A. (1989) Flora of the Lesser Antilles, Vol. 5. President and Fellows of Harvard College, Jamaica Plain, Massachusetts, 604 pp." type="book" year="1989">Howard (1989: 415)</bibRefCitation>
reports 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FD95BE489490AC40" authorityName="Britton &amp; Rose" authorityYear="1919" box="[517,721,863,889]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="wentiana">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FD95BE489490AC40" box="[517,721,863,889]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Opuntia wentiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FC89BE49953AAC40" box="[793,891,862,888]" name="Grenada" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Grenada</collectingCountry>
, the only locality he notes in the Lesser Antilles. This is supported by the specimen 
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FD9EBE9694A7ACA4" box="[526,742,897,924]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">R.A.Howard 18335</emphasis>
(A01677346!) collected at Pointe Saline. We failed to find this species on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B08FFC5FE91BEB29721AC87" box="[257,352,933,959]" name="Grenada" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">Grenada</collectingCountry>
and we believe Howard’s specimen is probably a weakly-spined form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B08FFC5FB1BBEB292BAAC87" authorityName="Haworth" authorityYear="1819" baseAuthorityName="Ker Gawler" box="[1163,1275,933,959]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dillenii">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B08FFC5FB1BBEB292BAAC87" box="[1163,1275,933,959]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="50">O. dillenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, either growing in poor conditions or showing juvenile characteristics.
</paragraph>
